Computer vision - Application of Convolutional Neural Network to image classification, glasses vs no glasses¶

In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
import os
import shutil
import random

The original dataset used for this project was found on kaggle: Glasses or No Glasses - https://www.kaggle.com/jeffheaton/glasses-or-no-glasses¶

However, after the process of data-cleaning I found out that the classes were imbalanced (more photos were glasses than not_glasses)¶

I decided to use one additional dataset from Kaggle: 1 Million Fake Faces - 1 - https://www.kaggle.com/tunguz/1-million-fake-faces, from which I took 311 adittional photos belonging to the class no_glasses¶

It is important to mention that in both datasets the images were created artificially¶

1)Data reading and preparation¶

This part will be just shown in one photo located in the folder test, in order to show how the process looks like. However, in the project it was done in the main folder were all the images were located¶

In [2]:
dir_ = "/Users/Lajobu/Desktop/test"

The data does not have labels, this means we don't know which images are part of the group glasses or no_glasses. For this reason the first step in the process will be to create labels¶

Firstly, the file names and extensions are going to be extracted. After that, it will be appended to the directory addres dir_¶

In [3]:
import os
file = []
for root, dirs, files in os.walk(dir_):
    for filename in files:
        file.append(dir_+"/"+filename)

The photos from the second dataset 1 Million Fake Faces - 1 had different format than the original dataset, hence I decided to change the format, from png to jpg¶

This was done with the package PIL¶

In [4]:
from PIL import Image 
for i in range(len(file)):
    try:
        Image.open(file[i]).save(file[i][:-3] + 'jpg')
    except:
        pass

At this stage we are able to create the labels of the photos. I decided to create three different categories:¶

  • glasses
  • no_glasses
  • not_clear: As mentioned before the images were created artificially, hence some photos it was not clear wheter the photos belong to the class glasses or no_glasses

The not_clear class will not be used in the model¶

2) Creating labels:¶

In [5]:
from pigeonXT import annotate
from IPython.display import display, Image

It is important to import the above packages at this stage, because it could create a conflict with the package PIL¶

2.1) Creating annotations¶

With the help of the package pigeonXT we are going to create a list of annotations ann. The created tool is based on pigeon-jupyter 0.1.0 documentation - https://pypi.org/project/pigeon-jupyter/¶

In each call the tool runs a batch of 200 images, and we should just select the button according to the class¶

In [6]:
ann = annotate(
  file[0:200],
  options=['glasses', 'no_glasses', 'not_clear'],
  display_fn=lambda filename: display(Image(filename, width=350, height=100))
)

2.2) Moving the images¶

After the list ann is created with the anotation of the 200 batches, we are ready to move the images from the general dir_folder to the one created for each class glasses, no_glasses and not_clear¶

In [7]:
for k, v in ann.items():
    if v == "glasses":
        shutil.move(k, "/Users/Lajobu/Desktop/Projects/DL/Classificastion/Images/glasses")
    elif v == "no_glasses":
        shutil.move(k, "/Users/Lajobu/Desktop/Projects/DL/Classificastion/Images/no_glasses")
    else:
         shutil.move(k, "/Users/Lajobu/Desktop/Projects/DL/Classificastion/Images/not_clear")

This process should be done several times, as there are more than 5000 images¶
